    Jupyter NB - Ruby kernel¶

    I am developing IRuby a kernel in Ruby that adheres to the Jupyter/IPython messaging protocol. It integrates nicely with different Rubygems as will be shown later.

    What does this give you?¶

    This gives us a very fancy web notebook interface for Ruby. It's a very good tool for programming presentations. It's basically an in-browser REPL loop, with some extra goodies.

    Usage¶

    Install IRuby with:

    gem install iruby

    Start the IRuby notebook with:

    iruby notebook

    Example¶

    $stdout and $stderr are redirected to the notebook

    In [1]:
    Copied! 
    puts 'Hello, world!'
    puts 'Hello, world!'
    Hello, world!
    In [2]:
    Copied! 
    $stderr.puts 'Error!'
    $stderr.puts 'Error!'
    Error!

    The last computed result is returned.

    In [3]:
    Copied! 
    Math.sqrt(2)
    Math.sqrt(2)
    Out[3]:
    1.4142135623730951

    This works even for images.

    In [4]:
    Copied! 
    File.open('IRuby Examples/ruby.svg')
    File.open('IRuby Examples/ruby.svg')
    Out[4]:
    In [5]:
    Copied! 
    File.open('IRuby Examples/ruby.png')
    File.open('IRuby Examples/ruby.png')
    Out[5]:

    Display¶

    IRuby provides a method to display objects IRuby.display and methods to create $\LaTeX$ and HTML representations.

    In [6]:
    Copied! 
    IRuby.display '<b style="color:green">Hello, world!</b>', mime: 'text/html'
    IRuby.display 'Hello, world!', mime: 'text/html'
    Hello, world!
    In [7]:
    Copied! 
    IRuby.html '<iframe src=http://en.mobile.wikipedia.org/?useformat=mobile width=700 height=350></iframe>'
    IRuby.html ''
    Out[7]:

    $\LaTeX$ is rendered using MathJax.

\nabla \times \vec{\mathbf{E}}\, +\, \frac1c\, \frac{\partial\vec{\mathbf{B}}}{\partial t} & = \vec{\mathbf{0}} \\

    Integration with Ruby gems¶

    Pry¶

    Pry is an enhanced Ruby REPL. It will be automatically used by IRuby if available. You can use the code browsing utilities for example.

    Gnuplot¶

    Gnuplot::Plot objects are automatically displayed inline as SVG.

    In [11]:
    Copied! 
    require 'gnuplot'

Gnuplot::Plot.new do |plot|  
    plot.xrange '[-0.5:0.5]'
    plot.title  'Example plot'
    plot.ylabel 'x'
    plot.xlabel 'sin(1/x)'
    plot.samples 10000
    plot.data << Gnuplot::DataSet.new('sin(1/x)') do |ds|
        ds.with = 'lines'
        ds.linewidth = 2
    end
end
    require 'gnuplot' Gnuplot::Plot.new do |plot| plot.xrange '[-0.5:0.5]' plot.title 'Example plot' plot.ylabel 'x' plot.xlabel 'sin(1/x)' plot.samples 10000 plot.data << Gnuplot::DataSet.new('sin(1/x)') do |ds| ds.with = 'lines' ds.linewidth = 2 end end
    Out[11]:

    You can also create nice 3D plots

    In [12]:
    Copied! 
    Gnuplot::SPlot.new do |plot|
    plot.title 'Spiral'
    plot.nokey
    plot.parametric
    plot.hidden3d
    plot.view '80,50'
    plot.isosamples '60,15'
    plot.xrange '[-8:8]'
    plot.yrange '[-8:8]'
    plot.zrange '[-8:8]'
    plot.urange '[-2*pi:2*pi]'
    plot.vrange '[-pi:pi]'
    plot.data << Gnuplot::DataSet.new('cos(u)*(cos(v)+3), sin(u)*(cos(v)+3), sin(v)+u') do |ds|
        ds.with = 'lines'
    end
end
    Gnuplot::SPlot.new do |plot| plot.title 'Spiral' plot.nokey plot.parametric plot.hidden3d plot.view '80,50' plot.isosamples '60,15' plot.xrange '[-8:8]' plot.yrange '[-8:8]' plot.zrange '[-8:8]' plot.urange '[-2*pi:2*pi]' plot.vrange '[-pi:pi]' plot.data << Gnuplot::DataSet.new('cos(u)*(cos(v)+3), sin(u)*(cos(v)+3), sin(v)+u') do |ds| ds.with = 'lines' end end
    Out[12]:

    Rubyvis¶

    Rubyvis objects are automatically displayed inline as SVG.

    In [13]:
    Copied! 
    require 'rubyvis'
    
Rubyvis::Panel.new do 
  width 150
  height 150
  bar do
    data [1, 1.2, 1.7, 1.5, 0.7, 0.3]
    width 20
    height {|d| d * 80}
    bottom(0)
    left {index * 25}
  end
end
    require 'rubyvis' Rubyvis::Panel.new do width 150 height 150 bar do data [1, 1.2, 1.7, 1.5, 0.7, 0.3] width 20 height {|d| d * 80} bottom(0) left {index * 25} end end
    Out[13]:

    Matrix & GSL¶

    Matrix and GSL::Matrix objects are automatically displayed as $\LaTeX$.

    In [14]:
    Copied! 
    require 'matrix'
Matrix[[1,2,3],[1,2,3]]
    require 'matrix' Matrix[[1,2,3],[1,2,3]]
    Out[14]:
    $$\left(\begin{array}{ccc} 1&2&3\\ 1&2&3\\ \end{array}\right)$$

    Nyaplot¶

    In [15]:
    Copied! 
    require 'nyaplot'

x = []; y = []; theta = 0.6; a=1
while theta < 14*Math::PI do
  x.push(a*Math::cos(theta)/theta)
  y.push(a*Math::sin(theta)/theta)
  theta += 0.1
end
plot1 = Nyaplot::Plot.new
plot1.add(:line, x, y)
plot1.show
    require 'nyaplot' x = []; y = []; theta = 0.6; a=1 while theta < 14*Math::PI do x.push(a*Math::cos(theta)/theta) y.push(a*Math::sin(theta)/theta) theta += 0.1 end plot1 = Nyaplot::Plot.new plot1.add(:line, x, y) plot1.show
